commit_message:
Add experimental Rally jobs for Manila

To be able to test Rally scenarios for Manila we need CI jobs.
Create two such jobs and add them to experimental queue.

Change-Id: I5b68894e52d9c1996e304d2744856dcf7373b055

commit_message:
murano documentation and cleanup

project name muranos official name and capitalization changed
see: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/Conventions
removed unnecessary capitalizations throughout the docs
corrected grammar and vocabulary to follow standards
added “an” instead of “a” before words that start with vowels
corrected spelling throughout several docs

Change-Id: I43678b35bc8df289468900133816607a9fbda1cc

commit_message:
Revert "Support 'require_online' flag for roles on UI"

This change makes no sense as the deployment will fail with any offline node

This reverts commit 5cd6c1236c81faaf61d3ce1cd3c9ac9e13cf1056.

Change-Id: Icc72855fcd6267216253c513a203aa8a4f09e0c9

commit_message:
Don't pass read only attributes on neutron update

When making calls to neutron to update an IPv6 network
Horizon is passing read only attributes which fails,
making v6 subnets uneditable.

Correct the view logic to not include read only attrbutes
on an update.

Change-Id: I219337b54c1fc55c8012ba63dd57fc1bb00bc922
Closes-Bug: 1459446

commit_message:
adjust alarm post ut code to adapt to upstream wsme

wsme has upgraded from 0.6.4 to 0.7.0, and now it supports convert
int and str to boolean, which causes our unit test code failed.

This change adjust the affected unit test code to adapt to such
changes.

Change-Id: Ic0d098e8e689e2421f261a72744abc3da576d8b2
Closes-Bug: #1460869

[{'created': '2015-05-14 22:44:06.000000000', 'message': "Make blueprints doc a reference for nova blueprints

Previously  kilo.blueprints was a document to propose a change to the
blueprints process. Turn the document into a reference for blueprints,
specs and priorities in nova.

* Just state current policy instead of references to how it was
  before. This information will still be around in the git history if we
  never need to look it up.
* Now that we have been doing this for a cycle we don't need hypothetical
  examples anymore.
* Make this reflect the fact that we just use an etherpad to track
* priority reviews.

commit_message:
Make blueprints doc a reference for nova blueprints

Previously  kilo.blueprints was a document to propose a change to the
blueprints process. Turn the document into a reference for blueprints,
specs and priorities in nova.

* Just state current policy instead of references to how it was
  before. This information will still be around in the git history if we
  never need to look it up.
* Now that we have been doing this for a cycle we don't need hypothetical
  examples anymore.
* Make this reflect the fact that we just use an etherpad to track
* priority reviews.

Change-Id: I0d6e568fe1a8ef40de1d7f7d7e45260b1400e407

commit_message:
Prune development.environment doc

* Just point to dvstack docs
* Don't go into advanced tox features like '--notest' and how to source
  a env that tox builds. These are beyond setting up your environment.
  And are not very nova specific.
* Don't show how to build man pages, they are very out of date and
  mostly useless anyway.
* Drop 12.04 based install instructions
* We don't need libvirt-dev to run unit tests anymore

Change-Id: I3fab352e2d9d7cb64ebfe2603ec658768fdd0e44

we do a cleanup.

Also, do this before we add the line, so we don't add multiple lines on

commit_message:
Remove the lvm.conf filter during cleanup

This avoids us leaving the filter in the global lvm config. Without cleaning
this up, we can hit some failures to run stack.sh because devices are excluded
that we need to be able to see. This resets it to what it was before when
we do a cleanup.

Also, do this before we add the line, so we don't add multiple lines on
successive runs.

Closes-bug: #1437998
Change-Id: Idbf8a06b723f79ef16a7c175ee77a8c25f813244
(cherry picked from commit 6cdb2e0f1a2c2429587f1e9187344cb26eb31812)

commit_message:
Prevent node delete based on provision, not power, state

This patch removes a conditional that was preventing a node from being
deleted (from the DB) based on its power state. We should not care about
what power state the node currently is before deleting it but instead we
should care about deleting a node depending on its provision state. Say
a node is active or cleaning or zapping, etc... We don't want to delete
the node on those states because there are some actions being made at
those states.

Closes-Bug: #1461115
Change-Id: I9778898477c8129e1e98be066695bd96f8f660b8

[{'created': '2015-04-13 20:01:48.000000000', 'message': 'Raise baremetal.unprovision_timeout default to 5min

In Kilo, Ironic introduced Node cleaning - an optional (but default
enabled) step which is performed after deletion and before returning a
node to the available pool.

By default, this step will securely-erase the node's disks. While that
action is implemented as a no-op within IPA's ramdisk within the CI
environment, the "cleaning" process is still tested. Since this involves
booting the agent ramdisk during the cleaning process, the time lapse
between the delete and the node reaching the "NOSTATE" / "AVAILABLE"
state has increased to about 5 minutes (the time it takes to boot a
nested VM in the gate environment).

Change-Id: Icd5fe47bbaba189ef446f976f01309a7e3560a69

commit_message:
Raise baremetal.unprovision_timeout default to 300 sec

In Kilo, Ironic introduced Node cleaning - an optional (but default
enabled) step which is performed after deletion and before returning a
node to the available pool.

Devstack change https://review.openstack.org/#/c/168175/ overrides the
default to 300 already. This patch is just copying that default into
Tempest's config.

Co-authored-by: SHIGEMATSU Mitsuhiro <shigematsu.mitsuhiro@lab.ntt.co.jp>
Change-Id: Icd5fe47bbaba189ef446f976f01309a7e3560a69

[{'created': '2015-05-29 21:17:00.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes DiskInfoPollster AttributeError exception

If a NotImplementedError exception is raised while getting samples through
a DiskInfoPollster, another exception occurs, as it tries to access an
attribute that does not exist.

Replaces the usage of manager.inspector with self.inspector.

Change-Id: Ie1bb6eaffc0b2671f8fefb4771dbd2191eb5cf5f
Closes-Bug: #1460207
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes DiskInfoPollster AttributeError exception

If a NotImplementedError exception is raised while getting samples through
a DiskInfoPollster, another exception occurs, as it tries to access an
attribute that does not exist.

Replaces the usage of manager.inspector with self.inspector.

Change-Id: Ie1bb6eaffc0b2671f8fefb4771dbd2191eb5cf5f
Closes-Bug: #1460207

commit_message:
Fix ignoring the existent metadata

Fix the class test_snapshot_metadata tests from volume module to consider
the metadata already created for a snapshot.

Closes-Bug: #1379460

Change-Id: I78e6f0601d21dc25fa95dc35818c907f40a931a3

Tested on fedora:

stack@virtual-machine:~$ disk-image-create fedora grub2 -o /tmp/test_image
stack@virtual-machine:~$ qemu-img convert -f qcow2 -O raw /tmp/test_image.qcow2 /tmp/test_image.raw
stack@virtual-machine:~$ sudo losetup /dev/loop1 /tmp/test_image.raw 
stack@virtual-machine:~$ sudo mount /dev/loop1  /tmp/test/
stack@virtual-machine:~$ sudo chroot /tmp/test/
bash-4.2# rpm -q grub2
grub2-2.00-27.fc20.x86_64
bash-4.2# exit'}, {'account_id': 13362, 'date': '2015-03-27 02:34:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

This doesn't work with Ubuntu. Unable to create image.

disk-image-create -u ubuntu grub2 -0 /tmp/ubuntu-local-boot

Problem is the post-installation script. Log:

Creating config file /etc/default/grub with new version
grub-probe: error: cannot find a device for / (is /dev mounted?).
grub-probe: error: cannot find a device for /boot (is /dev mounted?).
grub-probe: error: cannot find a device for /boot/grub (is /dev mounted?).
/usr/sbin/grub-probe: error: cannot find a device for / (is /dev mounted?).
dpkg: error processing package grub-pc (--configure):
 subprocess installed post-installation script returned error exit status 1
/bin/df: cannot read table of mounted file systems: No such file or directory
                                                                             E: Sub-process /usr/bin/dpkg returned an error code (1)"}, {'account_id': 13362, 'date': '2015-03-30 06:04:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

It's the bug of https://bugs.launchpad.net/tripleo/+bug/1437548"}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2015-03-31 05:03:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Does the VM element not work for you? If not, can we break out the grub2 logic from there and then have the vm element depend on the element you create?'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-04-13 09:19:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi greg,

This is different, the VM element creates a full disk image (a image that has a partition table and grub installed in the MBR so it can boot).

This just install the grub2 package in the image (for partition images). The reason I do that is because for Ironic the local boot with partition images will use the grub2 from the image itself when installing it.'}, {'account_id': 11076, 'date': '2015-04-13 13:36:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

This will probably take care of only BIOS boot mode and not UEFI.'}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-04-30 04:59:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-04-30 04:59:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-30 05:32:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add grub2 element

This patch is adds a new grub2 element that installs the
grub2 bootloader on the image so it can work with Ironic's
local boot support.

This patch also modifies the iso element which was installing
same grub2. It removes the grub2 installation from iso element
and makes it dependent on grub2 element.

Co-Authored-By: Ramakrishnan G <rameshg87@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I37bcf2c525708d1e2e0f95cf5874a279f76861f7

commit_message:
Workaround Ubuntu bug: ifup is not executed for OVS interfaces

Interfaces are created in both modes simultaneously:
* OVS port (with additional OVS-aware directives)
* ethernet port (for executing at boot time)

Change-Id: Id17dd4b0f875643d21fdfd62cb0fc872078e0d95
Closes-bug: #1460972

commit_message:
Use EntityNotFound instead of ImageNotFound

There are too many **NotFound exception classes defined
in exception.py. This patch will define a general notfound
exception: EntityNotFound. And will use it instead of
ImageNotFound exception.

Change-Id: I2a09637be97905548b29673273e8579c69d42d52
Closes-Bug: #1461343

commit_message:
Remove dev-requirements.txt

Looks like a long time ago we used this to list development versions
of OpenStack libraries which have not yet been released to PyPI. We
don't really need this now. Do we?

Change-Id: I5f8fce7068ee8dba5817afbdd658650b6f2b74dd

commit_message:
Neutron main line compatibility patch for liberty.
 Neutron introduce a new parameter to the l2 OVS class a dict for bridge
 classes
 Add this param to the  dragonflow l2 class and created the br_int move
 object with the additional required methods

Change-Id: I79b2624c8e2a2ee2031e02c5075a23a60e26b993

The code works, but it defeats
Image uploads should always happen in the background 
https://github.com/openstack/horizon/commit/99aa842e978a6b377865cb9ca393a365bf8eb742

Django has a reasonably sophisticated file upload management scheme since at least 1.4:
https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.4/ref/settings/#file-upload-handlers

I'm going to take a guess you are testing with trivially/unrealistically small images. I think that's the case that demonstrates this bug. It is likely not new.

Rather than abandon the threading solution which is likely important in more realistic scenarios, I'd rather that you investigate identifying when the Memory vs Temp file handler is being used and clean up the file only when Temp files are being used. Maybe the presence of a filename is a good indication of this? maybe there is a cleaner/more direct check?"}, {'account_id': 9209, 'date': '2015-05-27 07:38:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Django 1.7 is different from 1.6, all UploadedFile objs are closed in another thread. We have to figure out a way to clone a new file obj based on passed in file objs in the begining of a new thead.'}, {'account_id': 9981, 'date': '2015-05-27 20:56:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Here's an idea that's potentially bad, but I'm going to share it anyway: maybe we can trick Django into thinking the file has already been deleted with a change like this:

diff --git a/openstack_dashboard/api/glance.py b/openstack_dashboard/api/glan
index 91fa883..461fbcf 100644
--- a/openstack_dashboard/api/glance.py
+++ b/openstack_dashboard/api/glance.py
@@ -130,6 +130,7 @@ def image_create(request, **kwargs):
     image = glanceclient(request).images.create(**kwargs)
 
     if data:
+        data.file.close_called = True
         thread.start_new_thread(image_update,
                                 (request, image.id),
                                 {'data': data,

I believe this stops the following close from happening:
https://github.com/django/django/blob/master/django/core/files/temp.py#L51

It seems that the Django code must have always intended to clean up the temporary file. It's not clear to me what was fixed in order to work around it, but it's our intent that we (Horizon) always delete the file: https://github.com/openstack/horizon/blob/master/openstack_dashboard/api/glance.py#L116

If this seems like too much of a hack to you it might be more robust to create and configure our own PersistentUploadFile and PersistentUploadFileHandler (based on the Temp one at https://github.com/django/django/blob/master/django/core/files/uploadedfile.py#L59). I think that might be too big of an undertaking. I kind of like the hack.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 9209, 'date': '2015-06-02 03:57:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 9209, 'date': '2015-06-02 03:59:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
I/O error uploading image

Fixed two errors when upload an image from a file.
One is the file name doesn't exist error.
Another is file got closed in a new thread since Django 1.7.

Change-Id: Ia64c385d89e0d938b14182f2744251f76b892eac
Closes-Bug: #1451429

commit_message:
fix node-get-console returns url always start with http

When we specify terminal_cert_dir in /etc/ironic/ironic.conf,
ironic node-get-console returns console_info url which should
start with https; When we do not specify terminal_cert_dir in
/etc/ironic/ironic.conf, console_info url should start with http.

Change-Id: Ief27e87a4f0f583954e54af6a03baf2c0b6d1104
Closes-Bug: 1458748

commit_message:
Remove unused novaclient.tests.unit.v2.utils module

This is an old carry over from pre-testtools days and has a nose import.
Nothing is using it so remove it.

Closes-Bug: #1458272

Change-Id: I01b5d35d2e2aec161bd3dbaecb4670ddf3ee8794

commit_message:
Add documentation on command deprecation process

Since we haven't removed deprecated commands before, add some
documentation to the devref on the process for this type of change.

Change-Id: Iff6f5df372bec524757b84747c7a95bbf6412c35

commit_message:
Don't use more than 32 cpus for network queue affinities

IF we have more than 32 cpus, discard any cpus > 32 for network queue
cpu affinities.

Closes-Bug: 1461306
Change-Id: I6aff2af39f25a32c710d5cdf9708dad6b2a201c1

Hi John,

Oh I see. But I don't think I agree with that, with 0.6.4 our tests are definitely broken, so it's clear that we either bump WSME or keep this workaround in our code to make it work. The dependencies should explicitly tells which version you need to run with current code on master, by saying >=0.6.4 is supported is incorrect.

Also, yea, pip will *try* to get the last version when >=0.6.4 is specified but there are many ways it can go badly, people can have out of sync mirrors, local cache, etc... I don't think we should rely on luck to have the right dependencies installed for our tests to work.

Plus, WSME 0.7 is fixing a bunch of other problems than this dependency one specifically.

commit_message:
Revert "Add simplegeneric to py34 requirements"

This reverts commit fe2f445418ad7cb7741a7d237fd2ad69c27833a4.

WSME has been updated to 0.7 which fixes the underlying issue with
'simplegeneric' not being pulled in as a dependency.

Change-Id: Ia224eafb2c2220c970367580a8818746f9479f9d

commit_message:
Prevent key error occurred on deployment history tab

Dashboard keeps app type on object model special key.
If type is needed to be shown like on Deployment details page,
it requested by that key.
But is the deployment was made by API call, type is not available.
So error was occurred.

Change-Id: I95d9bb23e0758b86ee503df17e97d041ac56a841
Closes-Bug: #1455529

commit_message:
Deprecate volume/volume-type/volume-snapshot CRUD CLIs/APIs

This deprecates all of the volume CLIs/APIs that go directly to the
cinder API via the volume service type.

This will emit a warning each time a deprecated CLI/API is used and also
updates the help docs for the deprecated CLIs and docstrings for APIs.

The plan is to do a release once this is merged so people start seeing
it and then we'll actually remove the deprecated CLIs/APIs in the first
python-novaclient release after the Nova server 2016.1 'M' release.

DocImpact: The volume, volume-type and volume-snapshot CRUD CLIs/APIs are
           deprecated and will be removed after the Nova 2016.1 release.
           Use python-cinderclient or openstackclient for CLIs instead.
           Use python-cinderclient or python-openstacksdk for APIs instead.

Related-Bug: #1454369

Change-Id: I4e92f924739de9b664e08117984bfb60359f2212

[Fix] Fix issues in verification.tempest.diff

Welcome back! Thank you for the update.

This doesn't really address the comment about "tested platforms." There's no information about how the platforms are tested, and the section may bloat if additional hardware support is added. Might be more willing to approve if that whole section is completely moved to a wiki somewhere with a more detailed explanation.

Additionally, it looks as though ProLiant DL580 Gen9 UEFI was removed as a tested platform without explanation, so I'm worried about what we would guarantee if a platform is marked as tested. If there was a regression and some sort of tests are failing now, we should probably know which tests are failing, or why that piece of hardware was removed.. In any case, having it in a wiki makes it more flexible and easy to modify in case regressions are introduced for particular platforms.'}, {'account_id': 10327, 'date': '2015-05-12 05:48:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Thank you Ruby and Mario for the review.

Mario,
Adding ProLiant DL580 Gen9 UEFI was a mistake. We have tested the driver on ProLiant DL360 Gen9. It does not mean it will not work on DL580, just that we do not have that platform to test.


Ruby,
It would be helpful if we could maintain the documentation at single place. I liked the option of hosting it on wiki only, but have few concerns regarding the same:-
1. It mean ilo driver documentation will go out of ironic source tree. What could be the impact due to the same; especially if somebody relies only on the documentation in the source tree.
2. Is it allowed to just have wiki based documentation and nothing in the ironic source tree.

Also, please note, have removed agent_ilo from the supported driver list for the UEFI secure boot. Though it should work fine as the code changes are common, but we did not find the signed whole disk images to validate the same.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-13 14:23:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

I generally agree with Ruby. I think this documentation is very useful but would like to see it live somewhere else like the the OpenStack manuals. I haven't read those extensively, but perhaps somewhere like this would be a good place: http://docs.openstack.org/developer/ironic/deploy/install-guide.html#setup-the-drivers-for-bare-metal-service

If we move this documentation there, it might be a good encouragement to move other operator-specific documentation there, as well.

Also, I really don't think it's good for us to say that something is "tested" without a clear explanation of what that testing means. A good explanation would be what features have been tested and how, when that testing occurred so that we don't say that this was tested against newer versions of Ironic, etc. That is the main thing I'd like to understand about this patch, location questions aside.'}, {'account_id': 13997, 'date': '2015-05-16 05:22:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Update iLO documentation for UEFI secure boot

Add documentation related to building signed ubuntu deploy
and user images. Also it describes the need for populating
boot_iso property for user image to be used in secure boot,
with Glance UUID of the boot ISO for iscsi_ilo driver.

Change-Id: I908dc14f1939bcc22ad646569ccf0002317fde91

commit_message:
Ensure metadata network works with DVR

As DVR routers use a different type of interface, this patch
amends the DHCP agent code ensuring that a metadata proxy is
spawned when the metadata network feature is enabled on the
DHCP agent.

(Cherry-picked from: ec408ac379108eee26d87a8d9834180db11877e0)

Change-Id: Id7f2e891c0753620a604cf6160c6b592db1aa284
Closes-Bug: #1447344

commit_message:
Adds floatingip allocate,release integration tests

This submission adds test_floating.py and floatingipspage.py which
tests allocate  and release floatingip functionalities based on
the new regions change.

Partially implements blueprint: selenium-integration-testing

commit_message:
filter the subnets which already in the router

When we already add the subnet to router,
if we click 'Add Interface' again, we can see
the subnet also can select, but if we real to
add the subnet, it report a error. We can hidden
the subnet if it already add to the router.

Closes-bug:#1417892

Change-Id: I485608d267b9b235c1e83a990e330dd1ca98f17e

commit_message:
Fixes a broken debug message in schema matching

This rather useful debug tool in the bowels of common/wsgi.py produces
a misleading message because, most often, the matching_schema has no
property called 'name'. Fixed it to print the schema in its entirety
because in most cases one would take the name and go lookup the schema
anyway.

The other way around would be to go and change all of apischema.py and
add a name property. This seemed to be the less intrusive and
disruptive change.

Change-Id: I4075bc911d2cc07cb6e7d98ffcff96441f7b3416
Closes-Bug: #1460033

commit_message:
remove cookbook-pacemaker from infra

commit_message:
Fixed flag setting error after data commit to storage

The flag "self._has_data" in method _post_commit() of class BaseStorage
can't be set to false after data commit to storage because method _post_commit()
is override in class SQLAlchemyStorage, which caused empty data frame couldn't be
insert to DB and make orchestrator keep retrying when a new tenant is created and
have no data to be collected.

Closes-bug: #1461359

Change-Id: I0d37f6da4c414ae19e67bb6dc1ba8d49a330f628

commit_message:
Huawei driver remove LUN controller change

* Change in huawei_t.py removes LUN controller change.
* Change in rest_common.py enables other volume
  type rather than only QoS volume type.
* Change in rest_common.py checkes whether the port is
  ok to use.
* Change in ssh_common.py choses the pool which have max
  continuum space to create thick LUN.

Closes-Bug: #1417068
Change-Id: Ie0a584ed65795129ebaca318325b87acdaaccd7a

commit_message:
Fix response when querying host detail by host name

When querying host detail by host name like
'wanghao-devstack-snapshot@lvmdriver-1'
returned by host list command, cinder returns
incorrect result in 'total' block.
"resource": {
        "volume_count": "0",
        "total_volume_gb": "0",
        "total_snapshot_gb": "0",
        "project": "(total)",
        "host": "wanghao-devstack-snapshot@lvmdriver-1",
        "snapshot_count": "0"
        }
This issue is caused by 'volume_data_get_for_host'
in sqlalchemy. This has nothing to do with multibackend,
this is due to the introduction of pool support for single
backend.
Fix this by querying volume filter by host or host name
like 'host#%' in volume_data_get_for_host.

Change-Id: I751a474677d50e552d87fe06fadfed45e3c1ddab
Closes-Bug: #1429787

commit_message:
Implement KEMPtechnologies lbaas driver v2 shim

Added the passthrough shim driver for KEMP appliances.
Updated the config file with the KEMP path to the driver.
Added unit tests to test the shim.

Change-Id: Ib429c8ebde4d2cbb54ad37f4bfe6e4255706479b
Closes-bug: 1436781

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-16 04:56:07.000000000', 'message': "Don't store expire into memcache

The expiry time that we store in the cache is in no way linked to the
memcache expiry time for the object. The expiry time is stored in cache
and then checked during the cache get so as not to return an expired
token.

This means we have two expiry checking code paths, one in cache and one
for checking regular tokens.

Modify cache so that only the token data is stored in memcache and that
expiry validation of the token happens in the same way regardless of
where the data comes from.

Change-Id: Ibe9816826e7d78b7ae25085f07ff9a2f18db9db0

commit_message:
Don't store expire into memcache

There are two times related to storing token values in memcache. The
memcache timeout and the expiry that is saved alongside the token. We
purposefully set the timeout to be longer than the expiry so that we can
cache that we have seen an expired token.

The expiry that is saved with the token is taken from within the token
body itself and tested for expiry before being returned from the cache.
This expiry is still present in the token body though and it means that
we have two different but exactly the same paths for where we test
expiry from.

Change the cache so that it always returns the full token body from the
cache. This way it is a drop in replacement for fetching the body from
keystone server or from within PKI and the token data is validated in
one place.

Change-Id: Ibe9816826e7d78b7ae25085f07ff9a2f18db9db0

commit_message:
Don't quarantine on read_metadata ENOENT

An operation that removes an existing .ts or .meta out from under another
concurrent operation at the right point can cause the whole object to be
needlessly quarantined.

Closes-Bug: #1451520

Change-Id: I37d660199e54411d0610889f9ee230b13747244b

commit_message:
bdm: Make sure that delete_on_termination is a boolean

Make sure that 'delete_on_termination' is always a boolean, even if it
was not passed in and thus got defaulted to None up until now.

This patch is really more of a pedantic fix, as we use objects for BDMs
everywhere outside of the API service, and object fields are of the
correct type.

Related-bug: #1370177

Change-Id: I2724bcbe159490f3bdd85f833412f3b20c4e1e23

Change admin_state_up to True when create port

VM can not get IP address by DHCP if the port's admin_state_up
is False.

commit_message:
Initialize new keystone-mapper project

Create a new keystone subproject called keystone-mapper, which
handles all the federated identity mapping validation. By
extracting this out from the server code we can more easily address
critical bugs as well as improve the UX of creating mapping rules.

Reusing keystonemiddleware ACL since it would otherwise be a copy
of it.

Source is at: git://github.com/stevemart/keystone-mapper.git

Depends-On: I2d0751acb4e2c56163360f92f149ca75bb381beb

Change-Id: I9234d9b65e142fb45f67afedcedde5e06dfe6c5a

commit_message:
Create new keystone-mapper subproject

The keystone-mapper project will handles all federated identity
mapping validation. By extracting this out from the server code we
can 1) more easily address critical bugs that arise and 2) improve
the UX of creating and validating mapping rules.

Change-Id: I2d0751acb4e2c56163360f92f149ca75bb381beb

* ipmi-test http://198.175.100.33/ipmi/185295/4 : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 12927, 'date': '2015-05-27 05:53:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@gordc, think more about this issue, could you please take a bit of time to look at my explanation about this patch:

1. For the requirements change:
I think rgw pollsters are similar to swift pollsters. In patch set 2, you said "not everyone uses ceph", same for swift, ceilometer(or basic openstack) can be deployed without swift, and we put "python-swiftclient" in requirements.txt:

https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/master/requirements.txt#L36

So, I suggest do the same for ceph to make sure ceilometer can load the rgw extensions at least.

2. What if user not use ceph:
If user not use ceph, then rgw pollsters are meaningless, so we need to auto disable those pollsters. In this patch, we raise PollsterPermanentError when the endpoint not found (indicate no ceph in user's environment).

commit_message:
Disable rgw pollster when aws module not found

This patch will raise PollsterPermanentError in rgw pollster
to disable those pollsters when requests-aws module not found.

Change-Id: I880ec77467fae026f25e61d04d7dd76e08834b08
Closes-Bug: #1424746

commit_message:
VMware: use get_datastore_by_ref from oslo.vmware

We added get_datastore_by_ref in oslo.vmware ver. 0.11.0, so we can use
it from there and avoid code duplication.

Change-Id: Ifaaf4a3d6a445eda6188569b8197f250620a9f64

commit_message:
Update the config drive doc to replace deprecated value

Supported values for the force_config_drive configuration option in
Nova are "always", "True" and "False", although "always" is
deprecated in Liberty [1]. This patch updates the value in our
documentation from "always" to "True" which is the right value in
the long run.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/156153/

Change-Id: I6005f058873b0b00991f43262bd48a796ee97d69

proper ISO8601 version.

Freeze rsrc_defn base on properties.data when restore

Get resource definition base on properties.data of
resource, avoid unnecessary changes.

- check-tripleo-ironic-undercloud-precise-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/19/159819/14/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-undercloud-precise-nonha/02770ab/ : SUCCESS in 55m 42s'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-06-02 13:05:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

@Shivanand:

The token is saved in a file and put in the TFTP server by the Ironic conductor so the deploy ramdisk (the bash one built by DIB) can fetch it and use to authenticate with the Ironic API. So it happens under the hood without the user needing to know about it.

The problem with this approach is that by Ironic being an admin only API we need to save an admin token to the TFTP, and this is an admin token that works with all other OpenStack services. So having this in a pure text file in a TFTP server doesn't sound like a good approach.

This patch mitigate this by having only the endpoints the deploy ramdisk talks to be public so that we don't need the admin token.

(There are other ways of solving this, for e.g using keystone v3 trusts mechanism. But that would need us to have a dependency on keystone == v3, which I don't think we can have right now because many people still relies on v2)"}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-06-02 13:07:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14: Code-Review+2

It LGTM, thanks Yuriy.

@Ramesh good catch on the bootloader endpoint.

I haven't tried this change yet, I will do as soon as I can and add my feedback here"}, {'account_id': 12356, 'date': '2015-06-02 13:53:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 14890, 'date': '2015-06-02 13:56:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-06-02 14:17:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-06-02 15:49:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-02-27 12:54:49.000000000', 'message': "Do not save auth token on TFTP serfer in PXE driver

Reasons:
1) Store admin auth token on the disk is big security lack.
2) Mechanism is not generic, only PXE driver does this.
3) IPA uses vendor API via 'acl_public_routes'.

Changes in this patch:
1) Token saving code removed from PXE driver.
2) PXE vendor method added to 'acl_public_routes'.
3) Unit tests of PXE driver updated.

This changes should not break PXE deploy because ramdisk
script can work w/o token (if vendor API method is public).
For future discussions: blueprint baremetal-node-secure-auth

Change-Id: I12cfdc0a8a7740cadd768068b91c258e028ef385

3) Unit tests of PXE driver updated.

script can work w/o token (if vendor API method is public).

commit_message:
Do not save auth token on TFTP server in PXE driver

Reasons:
1) Store admin auth token on the disk is big security risk.
2) Mechanism is not generic, only PXE driver does this.
3) IPA uses vendor API via 'acl_public_routes'.
4) Internal 'deploy_key' check used for iSCSI deploy.

Changes in this patch:
1) Token saving code removed from PXE driver.
2) PXE vendor methods added to 'acl_public_routes'.
3) Unit tests of PXE driver updated.

Change-Id: I12cfdc0a8a7740cadd768068b91c258e028ef385

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-17 11:39:08.000000000', 'message': 'Add nova object equivalence and ComputeNode changes

This adds a utility method called obj_equal_prims() to
nova.objects.base.py and a method called
ComputeNode.has_changed() to nova.objects.compute_node.py.

The utility method compares two nova objects for equivalence
by comparing their primitive representation, ignoring some
of the keys in the primitives. In particular it will ignore
the nova_object.changes keyword. A list of additional keys
to ignore can be passed in as a parameter by the caller.

The new method in the ComputeNode object determines if the
fields of an object have changed since the last time it was
checked.

The existing NovaObject.obj_what_changed() method determines
fields that have been set. It does not determine if the
values are different. The has_changed() method keeps a copy
of the object and uses obj_equal_prims() to compare it with
the current state and so determine if the fields have actually
changed as opposed to just been set.

These methods will be required when the resource tracker is
converted to use the ComputeNode object in a dependant patch.

Change-Id: I1b46878bd5d1172cca49b7a7bbb7cabb8a02ed11

commit_message:
Add nova object equivalence based on prims

This adds a utility method called obj_equal_prims() to
nova.objects.base.py.

The utility method compares two nova objects for equivalence
by comparing their primitive representation, ignoring some
of the keys in the primitives. In particular it will ignore
the nova_object.changes keyword. A list of additional keys
to ignore can be passed in as a parameter by the caller.

This equivalence method will be needed when the resource tracker
is converted to use the ComputeNode object in a dependant patch.

Change-Id: I1b46878bd5d1172cca49b7a7bbb7cabb8a02ed11

[{'created': '2015-03-05 19:03:05.000000000', 'message': 'Cleanups for pci stats in preparation for RT using ComputeNode

While converting the resource tracker to use the ComputeNode
object it became apparent that there was a trivial bug in the
way tags were assigned in PciDevicePool.from_dict() and that
the format for pci stats in the examples is wrong.

The bug was that a dict was assigned to the tags field and then
items were added to it as follows:

pool.tags = {}
pool.tags.update(pool_dict)

The setter for objects is over ridden to perform type checking
and coercion for fields. In the above case the tags field is
a dict of strings, so the coercion converts all values in
the dict to be strings (if it can). In the above snippet
the values of pool_dict are not type checked or coerced because
they are added directly to the dict. The correct way to do this
is (it just so happens that pool_dict again here):

pool.tags = pool_dict

The format of pci stats has changed so that extra_info is not
used. Instead the items are included without this extra level of
nesting. This is the way they are coded in the libvirt driver.

Change-Id: I8730f18d660777e23637b4846e06af1c3e14238e

commit_message:
Cleanups for pci stats in preparation for RT using ComputeNode

While converting the resource tracker to use the ComputeNode
object it became apparent that there was a trivial bug in the
way tags were assigned in PciDevicePool.from_dict() and that
the format for pci stats in the examples is wrong.

The bug was that a dict was assigned to the tags field and then
items were added to it as follows:

pool.tags = {}
pool.tags.update(pool_dict)

The setter for objects is over ridden to perform type checking
and coercion for fields. In the above case the tags field is
a dict of strings, so the coercion converts all values in
the dict to be strings (if it can). In the above snippet
the values of pool_dict are not type checked or coerced because
they are added directly to the dict. The correct way to do this
is (it just so happens that pool_dict again here):

pool.tags = pool_dict

The format of the pci stats does not include an extra_info
field as was originally planned by the author. Instead tags
that would have been in extra_info are included as additional
fields. The phys_function tag was intended to have particular
meaning but has now been dropped.

The api samples and related tests for hypervisors-pci-detail-resp
and hypervisors-pci-show-resp do include extra_info, so the
samples and tests are incorrect. This patch corrects them.

The change in the samples is not an API change, only
a correction, so there is no change to the API version. However,
the api samples are included in documentation so this patch is
marked with with a document impact.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I8730f18d660777e23637b4846e06af1c3e14238e

commit_message:
Update requirements to fix "python setup.py --help-commands" call.

On exec "python setup.py --help-commands" displayed
ImportError: No module named testrepository

Steps to reproduce issue:
% git clone https://git.openstack.org/openstack/python-novaclient
% cd python-novaclient
% mkvirtualenv pbr_test
% pip install pbr
% python setup.py --help-commands

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "setup.py", line 30, in <module>
    pbr=True)
  File "/usr/lib64/python2.7/distutils/core.py", line 138, in setup
    ok = dist.parse_command_line()
  File "/home/oleg/.virtualenvs/pbr_test/lib/python2.7/site-packages/setuptools/dist.py", line 271, in parse_command_line
    result = _Distribution.parse_command_line(self)
  File "/usr/lib64/python2.7/distutils/dist.py", line 464, in parse_command_line
    if self.handle_display_options(option_order):
  File "/home/oleg/.virtualenvs/pbr_test/lib/python2.7/site-packages/setuptools/dist.py", line 633, in handle_display_options
    return _Distribution.handle_display_options(self, option_order)
  File "/usr/lib64/python2.7/distutils/dist.py", line 669, in handle_display_options
    self.print_commands()
  File "/home/oleg/.virtualenvs/pbr_test/lib/python2.7/site-packages/setuptools/dist.py", line 393, in print_commands
    cmdclass = ep.load(False) # don't require extras, we're not running
  File "/home/oleg/.virtualenvs/pbr_test/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pkg_resources.py", line 2147, in load
    ['__name__'])
  File "/home/oleg/.virtualenvs/pbr_test/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pbr/testr_command.py", line 47, in <module>
    from testrepository import commands

This patch add to requirements testrepository>=0.0.18.

Change-Id: I26e54af15a8b3d41032ebd5aea982dec2d544946
Closes-Bug: #1412885

If every job has this listed it starts making the jjb files fill up with contact details.

Additionally often more than one person can help with a broken job. In fact, having a single point of contact could be very problematic as it may encourage single points of failure.

Would it be better to provide a wiki page (or similar) with a list of places to get help for particular jobs. For example, you could cover all devstack jobs by suggesting to enquire in #openstack-infra or #openstack-qa etc. The intention would be to have more broad/sweeping statements rather than per job.

Just my 2cents."}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2015-06-01 18:16:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Oh, certainly not every job will have this listed.  In Darmstadt we discussed that for certain jobs testing unusual configurations, on, say, nova, it would be good to have a point of contact for them.

We specifically would not do this for the standard jobs.

My example of adding it for the devstack-plugins is probably not the best, as right now, they only run on their own repos, so the generally don't need to tell their owners who they are.

This is more useful for the hypothetical case of testing, say, postgres or zeromq on nova changes."}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2015-06-02 05:11:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Add a contact macro

This macro can be used to record and output contact information
for jobs where it is not clear who is driving the testing effort.

Change-Id: I21083cee3c5d116b2438d8a6999ba60073ebda6d

commit_message:
Moving out the cisco n1kv section to stackforge

Since most of the n1kv plugin code resides in stackforge/networking-cisco
repo, it's best to move the n1kv section there

Change-Id: Ia26b504a4135b12f003a89e3f19ff650e0d271a4
Closes-Bug: #1441400

When parameter dhcp_server is None, we must use network gateway for each network. But because of incorrect use of variable dhcp_server, we use gateway of the FIRST network for each network.

Co-Authored-By: Roman Podoliaka <rpodolyaka@mirantis.com >
Co-Authored-By: Pavel Kholkin <pkholkin@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Fixed incorrect dhcp_server value during nova-network creation

When parameter dhcp_server is None, we must use network gateway
for each network. But because of incorrect usage of variable
dhcp_server, we use gateway of the FIRST network for each network.

Co-Authored-By: Roman Podoliaka <rpodolyaka@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Pavel Kholkin <pkholkin@mirantis.com>

Closes-Bug: #1443970

Change-Id: I9d22a2ac94e8675a231436ce8ba77260c4b8b98a

Add nova-idmapshift to rootwrap filters

nova-idmapshift is missing the rootwrap filter it needs to run as root.
This commit adds those filters.

commit_message:
Fix method signatures unmatching in db api

There are a few method signatures in db/api.py who unmatches their
children. For example `get_bay_list`

```
    def get_bay_list(self, context, columns=None, filters=None, limit=None,
                     marker=None, sort_key=None, sort_dir=None):
```

The argument `columns` is never being respected or used in children or
elsewhere. After collecting a few opinions we decided to remove the unused
argument `column` from the base methods in db/api.py.

Besides, there is another unmatch in db/api.py

```
def get_service_by_name(self, bay_name):
```

It misses argument `context` compared to its only child in
db/sqlalchemy/api.py. This patch adds the argument `context`.

Closes-Bug: #1459662
Change-Id: If4f60661c9cd182d6bbe4539b3c594fb45744874

commit_message:
Backup new resource as soon as possible

The root cause came discussion in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/175868/.
It is better to copy a new resources that appears during
stack-update to backup stack as soon as possible because
it reduces time when backup stack is not synchronized with
the existing stack.

Change-Id: If104037225905dc9c504972864270d6e68e08d73

[{'created': '2015-03-24 17:01:54.000000000', 'message': "WIP Convergence: Check-Resource skeleton

Currently, the patch does the following:

Kicks off workflow from stack.update_or_create:
  Once the dependency graph is calculated, the leaves
  of the graph are all casted into the RPC worker bus.

Worker RPC check_resource worfklow:
  Workers will then start working on each resource
  individually. Once a resource operation is finished,
  sync points are used to check if the parent resource
  can be worked on. Resources that finish early will
  wait for their siblings to finish. The sibling that
  finishes last will trigger the creation/updation/deletion
  of it's parent. This process then goes on for all nodes
  until the roots of the graph are processed.

Marks stack as complete when roots have finished.
  Once the roots of the graph are successfully processed,
  the previous raw template which was needed for rollback
  in case something went wrong will now be deleted from the
  database. The stack is then marked as complete.

Largely follows the convergence prototype code in
github.com/zaneb/heat-convergence-prototype/blob/resumable/converge/converger.py

PS: Could also be broken into more patches if really necessary.

Implements blueprint convergence-check-workflow

Change-Id: I67cfdc452ba406198c96afba57aa4e756408105d

commit_message:
Convergence: Check-Resource skeleton

Currently, the patch does the following:

Kicks off workflow from stack.update_or_create:
  Once the dependency graph is calculated, the leaves
  of the graph are all casted into the RPC worker bus.

Worker RPC check_resource worfklow:
  Workers will then start working on each resource
  individually. Once a resource operation is finished,
  sync points are used to check if the parent resource
  can be worked on. Resources that finish early will
  wait for their siblings to finish. The sibling that
  finishes last will trigger the creation/updation/deletion
  of it's parent. This process then goes on for all nodes
  until the roots of the graph are processed.

Marks stack as complete when roots have finished.
  Once the roots of the graph are successfully processed,
  the previous raw template which was needed for rollback
  in case something went wrong will now be deleted from the
  database. The stack is then marked as complete.

Largely follows the convergence prototype code in
github.com/zaneb/heat-convergence-prototype/blob/resumable/converge/converger.py

Implements blueprint convergence-check-workflow

Change-Id: I67cfdc452ba406198c96afba57aa4e756408105d

commit_message:
Add functional test for neutron port

Patch covers several common update cases:
 - update replace when port has not assigned ip and it will be
   changed
 - update replace port with assigned fixed ip - will raise a Error
 - update in-place, with changing any update_allowed property

Related-Bug: #1455100

Change-Id: Ibd133db87f210916c1609b36343d93f165b37677

commit_message:
JSCS cleanup - Angular framework widgets (partial)

We need to do cleanup before we can enable JSCS globally
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/185725/). Files also
cleaned up to follow John Papa's style guide.

Widgets cleaned up in this patch:
- action-list
- charts
- help-panel

Change-Id: Ie2ef890cc4dfb1d3630a191499225bf9321ec6d0
Implements: blueprint jscs-cleanup

added description column in vpn tables

In vpn tables 'description' column is missing.

This patch added the 'description' column in all the vpn tables.

Change-Id: I5dd6ebf34f0e4dc80daed67f938900572e763d5c

[{'created': '2015-05-13 22:19:55.000000000', 'message': 'Fix bug in install_vertica

If install_vertica or create_db fails on the vertica cluster,
the error is now raised and is reflected in the logs.

The trove cluster instances now display the ERROR state
instead of SHUTDOWN, trove guest does not timeout.

commit_message:
Fix create Vertica cluster or instance to show ERROR on failure

If install_vertica or create_db fails on the vertica
cluster or instance, a RuntimeError is now raised

Updated create_db unittest and install_vertica unittest
according to the new raised exceptions

The trove cluster instances now display the ERROR state
instead of SHUTDOWN, trove guest does not timeout.

Change-Id: I7e7ad80fbb7b7d20af97c2e68baf9ea32bb7e130
Closes-Bug: #1454851

commit_message:
Cast nova server object to dict after refetch

When we assign a floating ip to a server, we re-fetch it from the cloud
so that the metadata is all correct. However, we weren't doing
obj_to_dict on it like all of the other code paths that return out of
create_server - which means that it bombs out on
get_hostvars_from_server if subsequently passed to it.

Change-Id: I3f69f525b7d57ec91f70b77cdbd62aed9816f17d

commit_message:
Add neutron SQL tuning

Add variables for the following 3 neutron.conf vars:
- max_overflow (default 10)
- max_pool_size (default 5)
- pool_timeout (default 30)

This allows for sql tuning to better support bulk operations
(boot/delete) with the ability to define custom values in
neutron.conf based on business needs

Moved variables back to:
rpc_deployment/playbooks/vars/openstack_service_vars/neutron_server.yml

Change-Id: I9770b9720a18be224d27677d2fe07e5d8d38a360
Closes-Bug: #1461184

commit_message:
Change Credentials header to Blob from data

The payload data of credentials is the unfortunately named blob.
Currently when listing credentials the payload is excluded as OSC is
looking for a column called data which does not exist.

Change-Id: I6fa4579d7ec9ba393ede550191dbd8aa29767bf4

Partial-bug: #1461182

commit_message:
Ensure rpc_response_timeout is registered before using it

The response code in the rabbit driver doesn't use a Client object, so
the option is not being registered in servers that don't instantiate
Client instances (ironic-conductor, for example).

Change-Id: I7def5e6d4960938a17344db024585a0492d6969d
Partial-bug: #1461182

commit_message:
Cleanup OperatorCloud doc errors/warnings

Some of the OperatorCloud method docstrings were generating sphinx
warnings, and the output just didn't look good. This cleans up the
warnings and makes things pretty.

Change-Id: I8be7acc9872d18b7ba899d75ba3dff43dc600731

commit_message:
Update docs layout

* Explain these docs are for trunk (copied from ironic)
* All the docs in this repo are meant to be developer docs, so having a
  devref inside of the docs is redundant and just makes the docs more
  complicated to navigate. Move everything out of the devref folder and
  link to everything from main index.
* Move man pages into separate section. The man pages are pretty sparse
* right now, we should either make them useful or just delete them
* Remove dead docs from unused_docs list in doc/source/conf.py
* Shuffle docs landing page, move common referees to the top (API,
  hypervisor support matrix), Add a introduction section and more. The
  hope is the updated layout makes this document easier to navigate.
* Use maxdepth of 1
* Rename a few sections with what are hopefully better names

The next step is to prune out outdated documents and further cleanup
this page.

Change-Id: Iff453e47ccc902a0e72b1a5f6ce1ee939ff3a1a0

commit_message:
Extending test coverage for core components

'Second-layer' pass at extending coverage for core Angular components.
These are components that have > 50% coverage but can be improved.

Partial-Bug: 1435869

[{'created': '2015-06-01 17:11:21.000000000', 'message': "Fix cinder concurrency issues on rtstool

Since there's no synchronized access to configfs in rtslib it can happen
that rtstool or rtslib access an element that no longer exists because
it has been removed just in the middle of a loop by another Cinder
request.

This results in quite a different number of exceptions:
- .dump()
- KeyError
- IOError
- RTSLibError on storage_object

This patch synchronizes access to all rtstool calls that access or
modify configfs using utils.synchronized decorator.

Change-Id: I341a10da54ab01be68a0cae843f35e5c841c6d81
Closes-Bug: #1460692
"}]
commit_message:
Fix cinder concurrency issues on rtstool

Since there's no synchronized access to configfs in rtslib it can happen
that rtstool or rtslib access an element that no longer exists because
it has been removed just in the middle of a loop by another Cinder
request.

This results in quite a different number of exceptions:
- .dump()
- KeyError
- IOError
- RTSLibError on storage_object

This patch synchronizes access to all rtstool calls that access or
modify configfs using utils.synchronized decorator.

Change-Id: I341a10da54ab01be68a0cae843f35e5c841c6d81
Closes-Bug: #1460692

commit_message:
Don't update floating IP status if no change

The floating IP status was going through all of the
status update code every time the L3 agent sent in
an update, even if the status didn't change.

This patch skips sending updates to the server if the
agent doesn't change the status.

Change-Id: Ic3736bed3dc3e4ccb91f4acfabbf033949e09ce0
Partial-Bug: #1445412

commit_message:
Fix cert tasks not being scheduled for retry

Certificate tasks that are waiting for a CA to generate certificates
were not being retried. This CR fixes that bug, introduced as part of
properly handling exceptions raised during the worker service
processes. This CR also beefs up unit testing around this issue so
that this issue is not re-introduced later.

Change-Id: I0a506c67be7881cf8c781c534f332f1f8122161e
Closes-Bug: #1460873

commit_message:
Add a get_conn method to SwiftService

Because the implementation was a public function and not a method of the
object, one could not sub-class SwiftService to change what parameters are
used for connecting to Swift. With this change, one can do that easily.

Change-Id: I3c39ae05f25a053b4f4a03ffbedaccf4d135a75e
Closes-Bug: #1461194

commit_message:
Move compute limits to new _get API

This change moves the retrieval of compute limits to fit with the new
get API through a combination of the method name (which was using the
style we use for list APIs) and its application.

Change-Id: I758d5056d9fcb20289a2fe5587800459ff8eac29

commit_message:
Add EC2 CRUD credential support to v3 API

The keystone V3 API ships with EC2 in the pipeline by default. The CRUD
manager is available for the V2 API and we should also make it available
for v3.

commit_message:
Add rw functional tests for shares metadata

Add base client methods for handling of shares metadata and use them in
rw functional tests.

Partially implements bp rw-functional-tests

Change-Id: Icbeb0d92fba74814f0b6efd664db791518f27743

commit_message:
Refactor plan creation out of app-create

The work of collecting and verifying planfile contents
is causing the app-create code to bloat.
This is one approach to reducing that complexity.

Change-Id: I4a26f146fd89edc1c5d297590431c34405e90765

commit_message:
ironic-discoverd to be renamed to ironic-inspector

On the Summit we decided to rename ironic-discoverd to avoid
controversial term "discovery" which ironic-discoverd actually
does not conduct as per upstream definition.

Also proposed is new repository to split away client library
from ironic-discoverd/inspector tree.

Also notes that ironic-inspector has stable branches (named
stable/MAJ.MIN).

Change-Id: I3fed2fd7999cc7e8c81015b789d9efcebf22e770

commit_message:
Do not assume http expected_codes ordering

This fixes the unit tests[1] that breaks with a randomized
PYTHONHASHSEED (see the bug report).

The test assumed that expected_codes had elements in particular order.
Found with PYTHONHASHSEED=1.

The fix refactors the test case by injecting values using the same
ordering.

[1] neutron_lbaas.tests.unit.services.loadbalancer.drivers.haproxy.\
    test_jinja_cfg

Partial-bug: #1348818

Note: There are several other unrelated unit tests that also break with
a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED, but they are not addressed here. They will
be addressed in separate patches.

Change-Id: I5d761c392bf37a0b3626abc64e0e428f978638df

commit_message:
Redirect fuel-logrotate's pgrep output to /dev/null

On Ubuntu nodes, root's mail spool occasionally gets cluttered by
mysterious numbers coming from fuel-logrotate. Some might think it's a
message from aliens, but in fact Ubuntu symlinks /bin/sh (which is used in
script's shebang) to fully POSIX-compliant dash. It doesn't understand
'&>' syntax, is custom bash extension. It has been replaced with proper,
portable redirection.

Change-Id: I43d135b341fd83eaed35d92d3e93eec9610d6af9
Closes-Bug: 1461100

commit_message:
Change external resources to https where possible

This change updates all of the external URLs to use HTTPS where
possible. the change will create a more secure deployment by default.

Change-Id: I4d53c021904208bffb0d597c7ae53bbd00f40209
Closes-Bug: 1411331
(cherry picked from commit e6383147bfa1ecd24747f9bdf159e43e34625e49)

commit_message:
Make py34 job non-voting for oslo.messaging

We're seeing Bug 1367907 again, so disable the python 3.4 job for
oslo.messaging so we can fix a critical issue blocking Ironic.

Change-Id: I4f82ded404bb79581feb568685062fb224897b42

In line comment urging approval of this BP.

I see image properties and using them to filter hosts is a convenience for image/appliance providers, might come by way of an OVA or OVF or other format. Cloud operators could define and stick to a few granular flavors and the image properties help to fine tune. Prevents flavor explanation. Example features such as those mentioned here:
http://www.linux-kvm.org/wiki/images/0/0b/03x03-Openstackpdf.pdf.
This image metadata based filtering is important and the sooner it is available, the better. If the issue is not having a standard format, that problem may persist unless all vendors agree. Could we agree on a plugin for a mapper -- to map from one vendor value to another -- and should a libvirt style mapping gets everyone's support, no mapper necessary. For a first pass a libvirt style mapper plugin would take us in the right direction."}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2014-12-16 00:56:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-12-16 02:17:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified+1

I am giving a +1. We really need others to weigh in on how to handle flavor and image constraint mis-match. Operators and Nova community.
Folks, please see Dons and my comments on the this patch.

I reproduce mine for ease of reference: "I agree with Don on this one. IMHO I think some things should be binding from the flavor such as number of vCPUs, RAM, trusted etc, but other things could be constraints coming from the image properties. This has the additional benefit of preserving us from an explosion of flavors, because every extra spec modifies a flavor and we end up with a lot. More than a year back members of the Nova community voiced their concern on flavor run away. 

The real issue would then be ensuring billing comprehended the capabilities provided, essentially all the constraints satisfied to deploy the image.
This then raises the question of which features may override those on the flavor and which ones may be don't cares."'}, {'account_id': 136, 'date': '2015-01-13 07:18:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18:

There are other cases already where the flavor and image metadata are specified for the same item. The hw_rng and watchdog parameters can be specified on both, for example, although these are not used for scheduling.

At CERN, we see a need for both, with flavor tending to be set by the cloud administrator and image metadata coming from the application provider.They may be the same teams but in larger organisations, this is often not the case.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-01-14 10:05:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2015-01-14 16:52:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18:

Hi, Daniel, after more consideration, I think this BP does not bring any trouble to the CPU modeling.

This BP is different with the flavor's capabilities scope in extra specs. The flavor capabilities scope exposes the whole cpu_info data structure to the user, while the cpu_info itself is not well defined. This is not good and have been discussed in previous patch-set. We planned clean that messy, the reason that it's delayed because Joe Godon think it's too late for K release thus we postpone it to next release.

However, this image properties in this BP is only about the CPU features, instead of the whole CPU_modelling/cpu_info structure, to the end user. The end user can only set "capabilities_cpuinfo_features=xxx", so it's well defined and will not be impacted no matter how we enhance the CPU modelling implementation.

The only argument is nova may change the cpu feature definition in future, which I'd say that's not an issue. The CPU features definition mostly come from Intel/AMD spec and, in rare case, if not defined in Intel/AMD spec, come from Linux name definition. The hyperv have their own CPU features definition in https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/virt/hyperv/constants.py#L47-L59 and they are the same definition as libvirt side because they comes from CPU vendor spec.

Daniel, your idea?'}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2015-01-19 17:31:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-12-04 02:42:33.000000000', 'message': "More image properties support

Currently nova checks only very limited image properties like 'architecture',
'hypervisor_type', 'vm_mode' while an image can have specific other requirements.
An image may require specific CPU capability like AES instruction support, the
geo the instance should run, or some specific PCI devices. Nova should check
these image properties.

Change-Id: I1cef6d7e84500791b733db6ae2addf808ec8edd4

commit_message:
More image properties support

Currently nova checks for only a limited image properties, such as
'architecture', 'hypervisor_type', 'vm_mode'.

However, an image may have other constrainsts, to ensure optimal
performance, and/or to meet regulatory requirements. For instance,
an image may require a specific CPU capability such as Intel
AES-NI instruction set support, or be constrained to run in only
certain geographic localities because it uses a crypto algorithm
that may not be exported or because certain data may not leave the
country, or there is need for special purpose PCIe device support
such as for digital signal processing or crypto acceleration.

Such constraints are typically known by the image creator/appliance
vendor and readily provided as image metadata. Directly using such
metadata avoids the need to specify the same via flavor
extra-specs.

Blueprint: more-image-properties

Co-Authored-By: Bhandaru, Malini K <malini.k.bhandaru@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Jiang, Yunhong <yunhong.jiang@intel.com>

Change-Id: I1cef6d7e84500791b733db6ae2addf808ec8edd4

commit_message:
Display 'Topology' tab for failed deployments

Topology tab wasn't present for the failed deployments
since new verification was added before user can see it.
The problem was in the 'status' field which was empty because
Murano doesn't have separate option and message for 'deploy failure'
status.
Also, updated status messages.

Fixes-Bug: 1455154
Change-Id: I3dd1f8ffce6edbc86209e603247e5f1229384af3

commit_message:
Base64 encode the cert returned from the Dogtag plugin

Also, add the missing headers for the intermediates, and make the
algorithm match case insensitive to make the supports() method more
robust.

Change-Id: I728846494e8f60ca37640d9753081deefd6cb8e4
Closes-Bug: 1453636
(cherry picked from commit a42e35885ee21b78ca36aaee6f2e15002f6053cc)

commit_message:
Run Puppet HA and Ceph jobs for tripleo-ci changes

Changes to tripleo-ci can affect the HA or Ceph jobs, so these jobs
should be among the check jobs for the tripleo-ci repository.

Change-Id: I1ccf0b39cd63765ca69d22fd6f591a8d98cd2226

commit_message:
Remove the code against flushing public bridge

As unstack.sh does destroy all bridges, we don't have to refresh bridge
interface any more, as what is done in commit
c2dc95add6e46829f1705041c1d9dddab9b360d3. So in this commit we will continue to
remove the related statements in lib/neutron-legacy. These statements will also
cause undefined PUBLIC_BRIDGE error.

Change-Id: I4c7617f6a245ea4e2e08f518d873b1b8adc2b807
Closes-Bug: #1454475

commit_message:
Simplify add_user_to_group function

Current SLE12 and openSUSE13.X versions can handle usermod's '-a' and '-G'
switches so remove the special case.

Change-Id: If0f1390a0eb8f41ffffca74525a4648cfe8ea61d

commit_message:
Remove packaged rpm python libraries

We want to use the pip versions instead, only python-devel
should be needed.

commit_message:
Add missing libmysqlclient-devel dependency for SUSE

Currently devstack unconditionally installs MySQL-python, so
we need to have its dependencies available. Since this is
transitional until the switch to PyMysql happened, lets just
add the dependency for now to have devstack working again.

Change-Id: I638b5999d35a06eee962679b1cd95950bbf2b1d7

commit_message:
Modify ipset functional tests to pass on older machines

Production code uses ipset exclusively in the root namespace,
however functional testing uses ipset in namespace for isolation.
This poses an issue as ipset is not supported in namespaces on
all kernels and distributions (I'm looking at you CentOS/RHEL 7.1).

This patch changes the ipset functional tests to work in the root
namespace while taking care of cleanups.

Change-Id: I08b2f59197ed76e59b2e58b5a10820653e857cda
Closes-Bug: #1460220

commit_message:
Make nova-manage handle completely missing flavor information

If you have a really (really) old instance without any flavor information
stashed in sysmeta, then nova-manage will not be able to convert it to
a proper flavor object in extra. This patch makes it handle that case
by looking up the flavor by id instead. Not only will this facilitate
the transition, but will also ensure that any such legacy instances are
properly brought up to date so that going forward we can just assume that
they have all been converted (and remove some other places where we
handle the has-no-flavor-info case).

This involves changing the flavor cache to contain flavor objects
instead of DB objects so that the two methods that use the cache can
coexist. It doesn't much affect the _augment_flavors_to_migrate() path,
other than some mechanics and test changes.

Change-Id: I54a056d339d98bc4092af8cf9f4f5d24b882506b
Closes-Bug: #1460673

when running tox in a devstack directory where you have previously run tox
-edocs the bashate testenv will fail as the shocco code doesn't match the
devstack style.

eg:
---
E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '           2>/dev/null ||'
 - /home/stack/projects/openstack/openstack-dev/devstack/shocco/shocco.sh : L352
<snip>

"}]
commit_message:
Skip 'shocco' code when running tox

when running tox in a devstack directory where you have previously run tox
-edocs the bashate testenv will fail as the shocco code doesn't match the
devstack style.

eg:
---
E003: Indent not multiple of 4: '           2>/dev/null ||'
 - /home/stack/projects/openstack/openstack-dev/devstack/shocco/shocco.sh : L352
<snip>
27 bashate error(s) found
---

Take the easy path and avoid running bashate in the shocco dir.

Change-Id: I5b0155332ec994afaffc5c5961902281864cff61

commit_message:
Add repository for the User Committee's ops tags team

As discussed[0] at the summit, the ops tags team[1] of the user
committee[2] will conduct its initial development of tags
in a git repository using the gerrit process while the
discussions around where they will eventually end up (both
file-wise and display-wise) are conducted.

This patch adds a blank repo and standard ACLs to
achieve this objective.

[0] https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/YVR-ops-tags
[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Operations/Tags
[2] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Governance/Foundation/UserCommittee#Working_Groups

Change-Id: I2daf3569f7973c7a0ff750fc31f0778d6ccaeb09

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-22 00:18:04.000000000', 'message': "I18n team want to become an OpenStack Project Team

I18n team contribute to OpenStack translations through a translation tool.
Currently it's www.transifex.com, which will be moved to an openstack infra
owned website: https://translate-dev.openstack.org/ in Liberty release.

All the translations are saved and managed by the translation tool. At the
same time, the translated po files are committed to each project repo by
automatic jobs.

The translators contributions could be measured in translated words by the
report function in the translation tool.
Currently it's https://www.transifex.com/organization/openstack/reports/.
After it's moved to translate-dev.openstack.org, Zanata (the new tool)
support the translators statistics report too.

Change-Id: Ie564c1bc377b1d981259263238f71d8980acbbc7

After it's moved to translate.openstack.org, Zanata (the new tool)
supports the translators statistics report too.

Change-Id: Ie564c1bc377b1d981259263238f71d8980acbbc7
"}]
commit_message:
I18n team want to become an OpenStack Project Team

I18n team contribute to OpenStack translations through a translation tool.
Currently it's www.transifex.com, which will be moved to an openstack infra
owned website: https://translate.openstack.org/ in Liberty release.

All the translations are saved and managed by the translation tool. At the
same time, the translated po files are committed to each project repo by
automatic jobs.

The translators contributions could be measured in translated words by the
report function in the translation tool.
Currently it's https://www.transifex.com/organization/openstack/reports/.
After it's moved to translate.openstack.org, Zanata (the new tool)
supports the translators statistics report too.

Change-Id: Ie564c1bc377b1d981259263238f71d8980acbbc7

I like this.  It fulfills the obligation and lets us spend our valuable time debating other stuff.  It doesn't seem like additional projects will be needed any time soon.  This set of projects is already a sizable superset of what is being used in the current defcore work.

The latest approved defcore guideline is here: http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/defcore/tree/2015.04.rst

This guideline covers capabilities fulfilled by Nova, Glance, and Swift.  The next guideline expected to be approved very soon will include a capability for Keystone.

Under this proposal, the following projects would be included in the "tc-approved-release" tag, but have not yet been addressed in the defcore process: Horizon, Neutron, Cinder, Ceilometer, Heat, Trove, Ironic, and Sahara.

Another option would be to make it even more minimal and restrict it to what defcore is currently using (Nova, Glance, Keystone, Swift) and just add projects as they request them from there.'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2015-05-17 19:35:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-05-17 22:59:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add initial .gitreview file and cookie-cutter template

Bootstrap the futurist project by using the cookiecutter
template. So that the CI jobs have all the things they
need and it follows the patterns used by all other oslo
/openstack libraries.

Change-Id: I738f68448e64e14725afc5e9c998751e081e7f07

commit_message:
Allow configuration of Nova SQLAlchemy options

Add variables for the following 3 nova.conf vars:
- max_overflow (default 10)
- max_pool_size (default 5)
- pool_timeout (default 30)

This allows for sql tuning to better support bulk operations
(boot/delete) with the ability to define custom values in nova.conf
based on business needs.

based on commit 58212d9b8a7e692d49ae2852f349829355f93a2b

Change-Id: I2a9a0992d0c41435f45e30bb38fcb1d74b60c6ed
Closes-Bug: #1447389

commit_message:
Remove get_dhcp_port RPC method

This method was last used in Icehouse.  I think we can safely
remove all of its code and tests. Icehouse to Liberty rolling
upgrades are in no way expected to work so I just bumped
the RPC version and removed all traces of the code.

Change-Id: Ia545c5be7da80c919ad5bae6074bc1cc3aa89fa0
Closes-Bug: #1314534

commit_message:
Add wait time to refresh tokens

Add a random wait time between requests for a new token and
continue attempting to send metrics while waiting.
The Monasca client will handle retrying once, which should
catch expired tokens.

Closes-Bug: #1454432

Change-Id: Ifd2e4891c24dbb0a53ad7d074f5842893ce4eedc

After discussing with Randall, we came up with the following plan:
- split this patch into two - one to add the config option, and another to do the encryption of the hidden parameters.
- we can then merge the config option and I can base Ife448fdb72f2de56107a74d47cdb64effb97e615 on that.
- this patch and Ife448fdb72f2de56107a74d47cdb64effb97e615 are then decoupled, so neither is blocking the other (although both include DB migrations, so one will have to be rebased ;)

I normally wouldn't ask you to split this patch - it's not too big or anything - but in this case I think it will help decouple the two reviews.

BTW should we also rename the config option, given that it will now be encrypting more than just parameters (specifically, we'll now encrypt properties data because it may contain parameter values)?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-20 20:12:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

(10 comments)

There are a bunch of comments inline, but I also have a major concern over the DB migration approach. This could leave a lot of stacks unreadable in the interval between when the DB migration is run and when the code is upgraded. Furthermore, the user is unable to change the config option to enable encryption after the migration script is run.

It seems like we need to store in the DB an explicit list of which parameters we actually encrypted (rather than trying to infer it from the template and guesswork), and then have a heat-manage command to just encrypt/decrypt (independently of migrations).

Key rotation is also pretty critical if something like this is going to be used seriously.'}, {'account_id': 7230, 'date': '2014-08-28 21:58:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 18.'}, {'account_id': 7230, 'date': '2014-08-28 22:02:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

commit_message:
Encrypt Heat template hidden parameters

1. Add a configuration option to enable/disable template parameters
   encryption.
2. Encrypt hidden parameters before storing them in the database and
   decrypt on stack load.

Change-Id: Ie46c6a149f414f655600616da8deee463e55671c
Implements: blueprint encrypt-hidden-parameters
Co-Authored-By: Jason Dunsmore <jasondunsmore@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: Ic5b8afd5968a3ea9cb32069d289f3c59729d776e

commit_message:
Py26 for Keystonemiddleware on Icehouse/Juno Only

Only gate the py26 gate job on Icehouse and Juno for the Keystonemiddleware
repository. Since it is not supported to run very modern Keystonemiddleware
with much older services, py26 is no longer needed for Kyestonemiddleware.

This will allow us to cleanup the test-requires and other py26-specific
requirements from the project.

Change-Id: I316d3ec56ade662cb5deeca0d3d48230c878f35d

commit_message:
Add text to infra docs index

Add descriptive text to the infra documentation index page to help
people navigate to the appropriate documentation.  This moves the
manual into its own section, system-config and publications into
a section, and leaves the rest of the projects in a section.

Change-Id: I90360ac6822ac93b02fc3bc67b8115dbf750f385

Use zuul-cloner instead of git clone

Use zuul-cloner for more efficient cloning because it can take advantage
of the local git cache on disk

commit_message:
Honour ``service_providers`` in AccessInfo

Service Providers are integral part of V3 Tokens. This attribute should
also be reflected in AccessInfo objects.
AccessInfoV2 will always return None.
AccessInfoV3 will return list of enabled service providers if there are
any and None otherwise.

This patch also adds attribute ``service_providers`` to ``fixture.v3.Token
class``.

Change-Id: I3104373ea6ef65a69f988bcf882bd0838b475f6f

commit_message:
MongoDB database management commands

Spec for enabling various database management commands for MongoDB.
database-create, list, and delete will be supported.

Change-Id: Ifaf22fbc40ce3dea86aa06fbe83557a0ed16f4e9
Implements: blueprint mongodb-database

commit_message:
Libreswan driver support in VPNaaS

VPNaas is not working on Fedora/centos devstack.
Fedora/centos uses Libreswan(fork of the Openswan IPSEC VPN) for ipsec.

Libreswan needs nssdb to be  initialised before
'ipsec pluto' command, otherwise pluto daemon will fail to run

(cherry picked from commit 72e1f670fdca2138aa85703cb96eac473f6fb811)
Change-Id: I54558208b2aaa82bda09c0db96042d236eceba69
Closes-bug: #1444017
Resolves rhbz: 1213148
Upstream-Liberty: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/174299/

When we calculate statistic data from database, we print a debug
level log which says something like:

computed value coming from u'(<ceilometer.storage.impl_mongodb.Connection
object at 0x12345678>,)'

This message only indicates which type of database we are using,
nothing more. However the database type is specified by config file,

commit_message:
remove useless log message

When we calculate statistic data from database, we print a debug
level log which says something like:

computed value coming from u'(<ceilometer.storage.impl_mongodb.Connection
object at 0x12345678>,)'

This message only indicates which type of database we are using,
nothing more. However the database type is specified by config file,
so this log is actually redundant.

Change-Id: Ia52f2d5f74509999097151e6906b4233214d74eb
Closes-Bug: #1459911

commit_message:
Base64 encode the cert returned from the Dogtag plugin

Also, add the missing headers for the intermediates, and make the
algorithm match case insensitive to make the supports() method more
robust.

Change-Id: I728846494e8f60ca37640d9753081deefd6cb8e4
Closes-Bug: 1453636

commit_message:
Add allow_hosts to pydistutils.cfg

This should cause easy_install to only contact our pypi mirrors
when fetching packages.

https://pythonhosted.org/setuptools/easy_install.html#restricting-downloads-with-allow-hosts

Change-Id: I7f7847721c2e8c6299c7fe5ab20045e8bdbc5bd7

Add stable/kilo to openstack-doc channel

openstack-manuals has a stable/kilo branch, publish events on IRC.

commit_message:
Add Stackforge project Mercador, part 3.

This is commit 3/3. It depends on changes in

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186967/

Mercador is a project for OpenStack service federation,
building on the Keystone work in Kilo. The project is described here:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Mercador

Change-Id: I43ac027c130c8249a911a29e12857bf8638424e1

commit_message:
Run puppet-check-jobs on bare-trusty only.

The openstack_functions.py node selector functions uses the default node
specification set by JJB when running the lint and syntax jobs against a
puppet module. This means that if you use 'bare-precise || bare-trusty'
these jobs will can run on both node types. This is fine until jobs run
on precise start failing because the default ruby is too old. Pin these
jobs to trusty to avoid ruby issues.

Change-Id: I26fb516995d8ac3a8f6fbf666b207ca2e9c4da97
